1
00:00:02,625 --> 00:00:05,250
♪ Good morning, U.S.A. ♪

2
00:00:05,250 --> 00:00:09,125
♪ I got a feeling that it's
gonna be a wonderful day ♪

3
00:00:09,125 --> 00:00:12,125
♪ The sun in the sky
has a smile on his face ♪

4
00:00:12,125 --> 00:00:15,792
♪ And he's shining a salute
to the American race ♪

5
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:21,792
♪ Oh, boy
it's swell to say ♪

6
00:00:21,792 --> 00:00:24,709
♪ Good morning, U.S.A. ♪

7
00:00:26,709 --> 00:00:29,917
CHORUS:
♪ Good morning, U.S.A. ♪

8
00:00:40,291 --> 00:00:41,917
(bones crunching)

9
00:00:45,250 --> 00:00:48,583
(all screaming)

10
00:00:48,583 --> 00:00:51,917
I just made a killing
in the shock market.

11
00:01:02,458 --> 00:01:04,917
Time!
Reset the test course.

12
00:01:04,917 --> 00:01:07,083
(bell rings)

13
00:01:07,083 --> 00:01:10,083
(chattering)

14
00:01:10,083 --> 00:01:11,959
(groans)

15
00:01:11,959 --> 00:01:14,458
Deputy Director Bullock,
I had no idea you were watching.

16
00:01:14,458 --> 00:01:17,917
Glad I could be so impressive.
I'll take my victory muffin now.

17
00:01:17,917 --> 00:01:21,208
Make it... bran.

18
00:01:21,208 --> 00:01:24,291
I'm afraid your usual muffin's
been earmarked for someone else.

19
00:01:24,291 --> 00:01:26,750
Hi. Agent Duper.
Big fan.

20
00:01:26,750 --> 00:01:28,917
Agent Duper
not only bested your time,

21
00:01:28,917 --> 00:01:31,500
he did so with
a far better catchphrase.

22
00:01:31,500 --> 00:01:33,917
-What? Better
than "shock market"?
-Duper?

23
00:01:33,917 --> 00:01:38,250
(imitating Desi Arnaz)
Lucy, you got some
'sploding to do.

24
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:40,375
-(grenade explodes)
-(man screams)

25
00:01:40,375 --> 00:01:42,709
Oh, we're doing
accents now?

26
00:01:45,250 --> 00:01:49,125
But at the last minute,
God told Abraham
not to sacrifice his son.

27
00:01:49,125 --> 00:01:52,041
It was all just
a test of his faith.

28
00:01:52,041 --> 00:01:55,583
My uncle's doing 25-to-life
for sacrificing his son.

29
00:01:55,583 --> 00:01:58,000
Well, I hope he found God.

30
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,250
He sure didn't find him
in my cousin's stomach.

31
00:02:02,417 --> 00:02:04,333
-Hayley!
-Mom!

32
00:02:04,333 --> 00:02:08,250
This is my Bible class.
Please, dim your headlights.

33
00:02:08,250 --> 00:02:10,333
Bible class, huh?

34
00:02:10,333 --> 00:02:13,083
Hey, tell them the story
of how God was denied
his fruity cereal.

35
00:02:13,083 --> 00:02:15,500
No, wait.
That was the Trix rabbit.

36
00:02:15,500 --> 00:02:18,125
I get them confused,
because they're both fake.

37
00:02:18,125 --> 00:02:21,375
-When did you become so jaded?
-She's a harlot!

38
00:02:21,375 --> 00:02:24,375
-They should be stoned!
-Way ahead of you, kid.

39
00:02:26,959 --> 00:02:29,583
I'm telling you.
That Agent Duper
is out for my job.

40
00:02:29,583 --> 00:02:33,291
I always get the muffin.
Always! Damn it!

41
00:02:33,291 --> 00:02:35,333
Did you use
my "shock market" line?

42
00:02:35,333 --> 00:02:38,166
Yeah, and it died.
Thanks a lot, Larry David.

43
00:02:38,166 --> 00:02:40,667
Beep, beep.
Done with your
foot cream, Stan.

44
00:02:40,667 --> 00:02:42,667
I got most of it
back in the tube.

45
00:02:42,667 --> 00:02:44,959
Oh, for crying out loud!
Can't you get your own?

46
00:02:44,959 --> 00:02:47,250
Love to, but you won't
let me leave the house.

47
00:02:47,250 --> 00:02:49,875
So, unless you're gonna open
a Circle K in the dining room,

48
00:02:49,875 --> 00:02:52,083
looks like we're
ointment buddies.

49
00:02:52,083 --> 00:02:56,458
Oh, and F.Y.I., your roll-on
really worked wonders
on my 'rhoids.

50
00:02:56,458 --> 00:03:00,834
Great. Francine, this Duper
situation is out of control.

51
00:03:00,834 --> 00:03:04,500
Hey, why don't you invite
your boss over for dinner
tomorrow night?

52
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:07,500
You know, for some good,
old-fashioned boot licking.

53
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:10,083
Dinner, huh?
Great idea.

54
00:03:10,083 --> 00:03:13,750
Ah, cheap Chinese toothbrush!
They can make a chicken
taste like an orange,

55
00:03:13,750 --> 00:03:16,834
but when it comes
to oral hygiene,
they really phone it in.

56
00:03:19,792 --> 00:03:22,750
(fanfare plays)

57
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:24,542
-You bitch.
-Bitch.

58
00:03:24,542 --> 00:03:26,583
-Bitch!
-Bitch!

59
00:03:26,583 --> 00:03:30,000
God, they sure knew
how to write female
characters back then.

60
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,083
Look alive, people!
Roger, what the hell?

61
00:03:32,083 --> 00:03:34,542
If my boss sees you,
I'm finished.

62
00:03:34,542 --> 00:03:37,333
-(doorbell rings)
-That's him.
Up in your attic! Move!

63
00:03:37,333 --> 00:03:40,291
-Ah, now you're doing this?
-Yeah, I haven't
been feeling so great.

64
00:03:40,291 --> 00:03:42,542
Once it dries,
it'll chip right off.

65
00:03:42,542 --> 00:03:45,166
-Go!
-Can I just top off
my Chardonnay?

66
00:03:45,166 --> 00:03:47,875
-I'll bring it up later.
-Something bright
and summery on the palate,

67
00:03:47,875 --> 00:03:51,417
but with an explosive
finish--
All right, I'm going!

68
00:03:55,917 --> 00:03:58,458
Deputy Director Bullock,
welcome, welcome!

69
00:03:58,458 --> 00:04:01,917
We're so glad you could make it.
Where's your wife this evening?

70
00:04:01,917 --> 00:04:04,583
Handcuffed to a radiator
in Fallujah.

71
00:04:04,583 --> 00:04:08,417
She wanted to come,
but I do not negotiate
with terrorists.

72
00:04:08,417 --> 00:04:11,375
Hey, do I smell meat loaf?

73
00:04:11,375 --> 00:04:13,417
Hayley, why don't you
say grace?

74
00:04:13,417 --> 00:04:15,625
-I'll pass.
-Come on.

75
00:04:15,625 --> 00:04:18,583
You pray all the time
when Jeff comes over.
"Oh, God! Oh, God!"

76
00:04:18,583 --> 00:04:20,750
Yes, yes, she's very devout.

77
00:04:20,750 --> 00:04:23,583
Anyway, what are these
photos doing laminated
in our place mats?

78
00:04:23,583 --> 00:04:25,500
Is this Agent Duper?

79
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:29,125
Yes, and he's eating
a falafel, recreationally.

80
00:04:29,125 --> 00:04:31,291
-(coughs) Terrorist.
-Smith!

81
00:04:31,291 --> 00:04:35,500
It appears you've
gone to great lengths
to discredit a fellow agent.

82
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:38,166
I like your style.

83
00:04:38,166 --> 00:04:40,083
-(women on TV, slapping)
-Slut!

84
00:04:40,083 --> 00:04:42,083
-Slut!
-Slut!

85
00:04:42,083 --> 00:04:44,333
-Slut!
-Slut!

86
00:04:44,333 --> 00:04:48,417
-God, who do you have to probe
around here to get a Chardonnay?
-(continues)

87
00:04:48,417 --> 00:04:51,041
Um, uh--

88
00:04:56,125 --> 00:04:58,083
Idaho!

89
00:04:58,083 --> 00:05:00,041
-That's all 50.
-Idaho.

90
00:05:00,041 --> 00:05:03,542
-Well done, Smith!
-(gasps)

91
00:05:03,542 --> 00:05:07,625
Pardon me. I think I hear
my wife's pie burning.

92
00:05:07,625 --> 00:05:10,166
That's my boss out there!
Have you lost your mind?

93
00:05:10,166 --> 00:05:12,709
-No, but I lost my buzz,
thanks to you.
-BULLOCK: Smith?

94
00:05:12,709 --> 00:05:15,208
-Into the bathroom!
-(yelling)

95
00:05:15,208 --> 00:05:18,875
Smith, this might be
the Chardonnay talking,

96
00:05:18,875 --> 00:05:21,250
but I think this bathroom
is the perfect place

97
00:05:21,250 --> 00:05:23,959
to discuss your promotion.

98
00:05:23,959 --> 00:05:26,709
-Into the tub!
-Without my flip-flops?

99
00:05:26,709 --> 00:05:29,667
-Ah, no! Good God,
control yourself!
-(yelling)

100
00:05:29,667 --> 00:05:32,000
Stop it!
Oh, in my eye!

101
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,166
Smith, are you
under attack in there?

102
00:05:34,166 --> 00:05:36,500
-No, everything's fine.
-Stand back!

103
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:39,709
(grunts)
Good God, Smith!

104
00:05:39,709 --> 00:05:42,375
What the-- Oh!
(groaning)

105
00:05:47,083 --> 00:05:49,917
Thanks a lot, Roger.
How do you expect me
to compete with Duper

106
00:05:49,917 --> 00:05:51,709
after what
my boss saw in there?

107
00:05:51,709 --> 00:05:53,625
It's not my fault
I don't feel well.

108
00:05:53,625 --> 00:05:56,000
It's always something with you.
You've been nothing
but a burden.

109
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,041
-(gasps)
-Stan, please!

110
00:05:58,041 --> 00:06:00,959
Yeah, Dad.
Don't stress him out.
It messes with his stomachs.

111
00:06:00,959 --> 00:06:02,959
No! No! It's about time
he heard it!

112
00:06:02,959 --> 00:06:05,583
We're the ones risking
our necks here.

113
00:06:05,583 --> 00:06:08,125
Do you know what would happen
to us if the government found
out we were hiding an alien?

114
00:06:08,125 --> 00:06:10,792
Oh, but he doesn't care. No,
he just lays around the house,

115
00:06:10,792 --> 00:06:13,041
inhaling groceries
and pumping out pudding.

116
00:06:13,041 --> 00:06:14,834
Shut up, Stan!
Just shut up!

117
00:06:14,834 --> 00:06:16,792
Our lives would be
a hell of a lot easier

118
00:06:16,792 --> 00:06:18,458
if you were just gone!

119
00:06:18,458 --> 00:06:20,834
Oh, yeah?
Well, I-I-I-I--

120
00:06:20,834 --> 00:06:25,625
(gasping, wheezing)

121
00:06:25,625 --> 00:06:28,792
Roger, are you okay?

122
00:06:28,792 --> 00:06:31,333
Oh, bravo, bravo.
Quite a performance.

123
00:06:31,333 --> 00:06:33,375
Ladies and gentlemen,
Mr. Ethan Hawke.

124
00:06:33,375 --> 00:06:36,083
-He doesn't look right, Dad.
-Up and at 'em, Ethan.

125
00:06:36,083 --> 00:06:38,583
Time to make another awful
Richard Linklater movie.

126
00:06:38,583 --> 00:06:40,709
Just ignore him.
He's being a drama queen.

127
00:06:40,709 --> 00:06:43,041
-All right, everyone up to bed.
-It's 7:45.

128
00:06:43,041 --> 00:06:45,041
We're going to bed!

129
00:06:45,041 --> 00:06:48,333
Uh, "Good night, Klaus?"
Geez!

130
00:06:51,834 --> 00:06:55,250
Huh. What commitment!
Wakey, wakey, Mr. Hawke.

131
00:06:55,250 --> 00:06:57,375
Gattaca II finally
got its financing.

132
00:06:57,375 --> 00:07:00,041
-Dad, I think he's dead.
-(gasps)

133
00:07:00,041 --> 00:07:03,083
Well, then I guess he
wouldn't mind if I poke him
in the eye with a fork.

134
00:07:04,542 --> 00:07:06,417
-(all screaming)
-Yeah, he's dead.

135
00:07:06,417 --> 00:07:08,291
I can't believe
he's gone.

136
00:07:08,291 --> 00:07:11,709
He's up in heaven now,
bumming smokes off Jesus.

137
00:07:11,709 --> 00:07:15,458
-Poor Roger.
-We should have a really
nice memorial service.

138
00:07:15,458 --> 00:07:18,208
Out of the question!
No, I'll have to dispose
of the body,

139
00:07:18,208 --> 00:07:20,333
so the government can never
trace it back to us.

140
00:07:20,333 --> 00:07:22,583
Well, at least do it
in a way that honors
his memory

141
00:07:22,583 --> 00:07:24,709
and all that he
meant to us.

142
00:07:24,709 --> 00:07:27,250
Darling, it's me.

143
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:31,542
A double cheeseburger,
small fries and a Mr. Pibb.

144
00:07:31,542 --> 00:07:33,750
Not the largest.
The one right under that.

145
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:35,959
MAN (on speaker):
That would be the medium.

146
00:07:35,959 --> 00:07:38,458
(tires screeching)

147
00:07:42,083 --> 00:07:45,500
Can I get some ketchup?
Oh, no, it's already in there.

148
00:07:45,500 --> 00:07:48,000
I see it. I see it.

149
00:07:53,834 --> 00:07:55,834
(screams)

150
00:07:55,834 --> 00:07:58,250
Oh, that sounded
kind of effeminate.

151
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,208
Holy crap!
Can't a guy fall
into a stress-induced

152
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:07,125
hibernation cycle
without being
chucked in the trash?

153
00:08:07,125 --> 00:08:10,709
-Okay, calm down. Calm down.
Nothing to be scared of.
-(bird tweets)

154
00:08:10,709 --> 00:08:12,792
(screams)

155
00:08:12,792 --> 00:08:15,458
Ahh, get it off me!

156
00:08:15,458 --> 00:08:18,291
Wait a minute.
I can use this to get home,

157
00:08:18,291 --> 00:08:21,125
-disguised as a lady.
-(glass clinking)

158
00:08:21,125 --> 00:08:24,291
A lady who keeps medical
waste in her pockets.

159
00:08:26,834 --> 00:08:28,959
You call me, Dad?

160
00:08:28,959 --> 00:08:31,375
Son, I know you're
having trouble dealing
with Roger's death,

161
00:08:31,375 --> 00:08:33,583
so I thought
it might cheer you up
to help me burn

162
00:08:33,583 --> 00:08:36,583
every shred of evidence
that he ever existed.

163
00:08:36,583 --> 00:08:39,125
What? Why can't we
just hide that stuff?

164
00:08:39,125 --> 00:08:42,125
It's too risky. No one can
ever know Roger was here.

165
00:08:42,125 --> 00:08:44,000
Don't you have
any feelings?

166
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,834
Son, feelings
are what women have.

167
00:08:45,834 --> 00:08:47,417
They come from their ovaries.

168
00:08:47,417 --> 00:08:50,500
You're a monster!
I have no father!

169
00:08:52,667 --> 00:08:54,959
I'm not
a monster.

170
00:08:59,333 --> 00:09:01,709
So if I cash out
my pension right now,

171
00:09:01,709 --> 00:09:03,917
how much will I get?

172
00:09:03,917 --> 00:09:07,583
Oh, damn it!
That's a very steep penalty.

173
00:09:07,583 --> 00:09:11,792
So, basically, you're
telling me I'm stuck here
for two more years.

174
00:09:11,792 --> 00:09:14,208
Yeah, thanks
for nothing, Marty.

175
00:09:14,208 --> 00:09:17,500
So-So what is it now?
Your mother died or something?

176
00:09:17,500 --> 00:09:20,667
No, it was
a very dear, dear--

177
00:09:20,667 --> 00:09:24,041
He was like a pet.
You'll have to forgive her.
She's very upset.

178
00:09:24,041 --> 00:09:26,750
Could you say a prayer
for him on Sunday?

179
00:09:26,750 --> 00:09:29,583
You know, so maybe
he'll hear it in heaven.

180
00:09:29,583 --> 00:09:33,333
For a pet?
You're serious?

181
00:09:33,333 --> 00:09:37,125
Look, according to the church,
there are no pets in heaven.

182
00:09:37,125 --> 00:09:39,959
Eligible for heaven: You got
your men, women, children

183
00:09:39,959 --> 00:09:42,125
and apes who use
sign language.

184
00:09:42,125 --> 00:09:44,542
Not going to heaven: You got
your pets, your dinosaurs,

185
00:09:44,542 --> 00:09:47,166
your smart types
and self-aware robots.

186
00:09:47,166 --> 00:09:49,959
You ever seen Blade Runner?

187
00:09:49,959 --> 00:09:54,083
No, of course you haven't.
All righty. Can I validate
your parking?

188
00:09:54,083 --> 00:09:56,333
Wait a minute.
Roger was good.

189
00:09:56,333 --> 00:09:59,291
What kind of god wouldn't
allow him into heaven?

190
00:09:59,291 --> 00:10:01,667
This kind.

191
00:10:01,667 --> 00:10:03,875
That's your idea
of God?

192
00:10:03,875 --> 00:10:06,000
(chuckles)
Hey, kick your ass.

193
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,875
-(sobbing)
-Whatever.

194
00:10:09,875 --> 00:10:11,625
How do I get home?
How do I get home?

195
00:10:11,625 --> 00:10:13,458
Where the hell is
a trail

196
00:10:13,458 --> 00:10:15,500
of Reese's Pieces
when you need one?

197
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:18,125
-Hey, where you goin'?
-(screams) I'm not an alien.

198
00:10:18,125 --> 00:10:20,417
Back on the bus,
Mrs. Nesbaum.

199
00:10:20,417 --> 00:10:23,417
ROGER: Huh?

200
00:10:23,417 --> 00:10:25,875
Look, there's been a mistake.
I need to get home.

201
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:29,083
The home? No, we're goin'
to D.C. to see the sights.

202
00:10:29,083 --> 00:10:32,166
Haven't seen you
around the pill line.
The name's Gertie.

203
00:10:34,041 --> 00:10:37,625
Now don't you fret about that.
Happens to me all the time.

204
00:10:39,208 --> 00:10:41,542
What do you know?
It's happenin' right now.

205
00:10:43,875 --> 00:10:47,208
Morning, Jackson. Wanna help me
analyze some Al-Qaeda chatter?

206
00:10:47,208 --> 00:10:49,959
Actually, Stan, they put
Agent Duper on chatter.

207
00:10:49,959 --> 00:10:53,208
They bumped you
down to Al-Qaeda banter.

208
00:10:53,208 --> 00:10:56,500
MAN (on tape): So I'm trying
those whitening strips,
but they're not working.

209
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:58,834
MAN 2: Are you
wearing them every day?

210
00:10:58,834 --> 00:11:01,208
-Well, every other day.
-Well, duh. That's why
they're not working.

211
00:11:01,208 --> 00:11:03,917
STEVE'S VOICE:
Don't you have any feelings?

212
00:11:03,917 --> 00:11:07,291
You're a monster!
I have no father!

213
00:11:07,291 --> 00:11:09,291
(groans)

214
00:11:10,917 --> 00:11:13,166
What seems to be
the problem?

215
00:11:13,166 --> 00:11:15,333
Well, I got in an argument
with our dog.

216
00:11:15,333 --> 00:11:18,083
He expelled a large amount
of xenoplasm, and then he died.

217
00:11:18,083 --> 00:11:20,458
Am I a monster
for not feeling anything?

218
00:11:20,458 --> 00:11:23,500
Well, that depends, Stan.
How close were you to this dog?

219
00:11:23,500 --> 00:11:25,834
Well, we do go back a ways.

220
00:11:25,834 --> 00:11:28,625
-(alarm sounding)
-MAN (on P.A.): The alien
has escaped to Level 4.

221
00:11:28,625 --> 00:11:32,709
-Repeat: Level 4!
-(electronic humming)

222
00:11:32,709 --> 00:11:35,500
I'll check this lab
where the theremin music
is coming from.

223
00:11:35,500 --> 00:11:40,000
Don't hurt me.
I know it sounds cliché,
but I mean you no harm.

224
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:43,917
You're the alien?
Well, they said you'd be
bigger, and with claws.

225
00:11:43,917 --> 00:11:46,083
Oh, I've got claws.
Look how fat you are.

226
00:11:46,083 --> 00:11:48,125
See? Kitty can scratch.

227
00:11:48,125 --> 00:11:50,333
MAN: It's in the lab!
Let's dust it!

228
00:11:52,375 --> 00:11:55,000
Let's go, space chimp!

229
00:12:06,375 --> 00:12:09,125
(groaning)

230
00:12:09,125 --> 00:12:12,583
You saved my life.
How can I ever repay you?

231
00:12:12,583 --> 00:12:14,750
You got TiVo?

232
00:12:14,750 --> 00:12:18,125
Stan? Thought
I lost you there.

233
00:12:18,125 --> 00:12:22,542
Now look,
this is a safe place.
How do you feel?

234
00:12:22,542 --> 00:12:25,750
Oh, I guess I feel
kind of... sad?

235
00:12:25,750 --> 00:12:29,917
-And do you know why?
-Because I... miss him?

236
00:12:29,917 --> 00:12:34,458
No. Because
you're a lady!

237
00:12:34,458 --> 00:12:37,709
-(laughing)
-"Oh, yeah. I'm sensitive."

238
00:12:37,709 --> 00:12:40,875
-I am not a lady!
-Wait, Stan.
You forgot your purse.

239
00:12:40,875 --> 00:12:43,041
Oh, I swear I'd lose
my own head if I--

240
00:12:43,041 --> 00:12:45,291
Hey, I don't have a purse!

241
00:12:47,750 --> 00:12:51,792
Heaven, pearly gates, angels--
it's all a lie.

242
00:12:51,792 --> 00:12:54,583
When your parents die, they'll
be in a hole in the ground,

243
00:12:54,583 --> 00:12:58,208
worms slowly chewing through
their foul, putrid organs.

244
00:12:58,208 --> 00:13:00,208
Uh, don't worry, kids.
God is real,

245
00:13:00,208 --> 00:13:02,750
Jesus loves you,
et cetera, et cetera.

246
00:13:02,750 --> 00:13:04,333
Mom, what are you doing?

247
00:13:04,333 --> 00:13:06,250
Well, I just can't believe
in a god

248
00:13:06,250 --> 00:13:08,917
that wouldn't
let Roger into heaven.

249
00:13:08,917 --> 00:13:11,834
Hey, Hayley, since Dad's
a heartless bastard and all,

250
00:13:11,834 --> 00:13:13,875
I'm auditioning
new father figures.

251
00:13:13,875 --> 00:13:16,750
Should I go with
outwardly affectionate
Tom Hanks

252
00:13:16,750 --> 00:13:19,583
or consistently
underrated Jeff Bridges?

253
00:13:19,583 --> 00:13:22,875
Why are you worried about Dad?
It's Mom that we've lost!

254
00:13:22,875 --> 00:13:25,125
Steve, mein Kinderstrudel,

255
00:13:25,125 --> 00:13:29,166
there's an emotionally
available father figure
floating in front of you.

256
00:13:29,166 --> 00:13:32,333
-Really? You'd be my dad?
-It would be mein honor.

257
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:35,125
Now, here's your allowance.
Five bubbles.

258
00:13:35,125 --> 00:13:37,583
Ach! What the hell.
Six bubbles.

259
00:13:37,583 --> 00:13:39,417
Don't tell your mother.

260
00:13:41,959 --> 00:13:44,333
Wow.
The Oval Office.

261
00:13:44,333 --> 00:13:47,792
Just think of the history
that's been made
behind that desk.

262
00:13:47,792 --> 00:13:50,750
Not to mention under it.
(laughing)

263
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:54,875
-Here, have yourself a nip.
-Wow! Getting hammered
in the Oval Office.

264
00:13:54,875 --> 00:13:59,166
Hey, look! I'm Kitty Dukakis
in an alternate timeline.

265
00:13:59,166 --> 00:14:02,583
People, this footage was
captured at 1400 hours today

266
00:14:02,583 --> 00:14:04,375
by a White House
security camera.

267
00:14:04,375 --> 00:14:07,667
Sorry I'm late. I was getting
a piping hot cup of coffee.

268
00:14:07,667 --> 00:14:10,917
It's far too hot to drink,
but luckily my leathery
man mouth can take it.

269
00:14:10,917 --> 00:14:14,000
Sit down, Smith. Our analysts
have confirmed this creature

270
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:19,333
is none other than the alien
that escaped from Area 51
four years ago.

271
00:14:19,333 --> 00:14:22,542
-My eyes!
-He's alive!

272
00:14:22,542 --> 00:14:25,875
Naturally, recapturing this
fugitive is our top priority.

273
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:28,500
Then we can track down
the bastards

274
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:31,166
that have been harboring it
and punish them brutally!

275
00:14:31,166 --> 00:14:35,125
-(man screams)
-I mean really brutally.

276
00:14:35,125 --> 00:14:38,333
Weird stuff. Butt stuff.

277
00:14:38,333 --> 00:14:42,375
-(man screams)
-Somebody take Smith's coffee.

278
00:14:42,375 --> 00:14:44,750
(horn honking)

279
00:14:44,750 --> 00:14:48,583
-(patriotic ring tone)
-Smith. Talk.

280
00:14:48,583 --> 00:14:52,083
Stan, you lantern-jawed
Sasquatch!

281
00:14:52,083 --> 00:14:54,834
You throw any of your kids
in the garbage today?

282
00:14:54,834 --> 00:14:57,000
Roger, I've been looking
for you. Where are you?

283
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,542
Oh, I'm getting by
just fine on my own.

284
00:14:59,542 --> 00:15:01,625
And I got--
I got something to say--

285
00:15:01,625 --> 00:15:04,750
-Call him a carpetbagger!
-You're a carpetbagger, Stan!

286
00:15:04,750 --> 00:15:06,792
You know that?
What's that?

287
00:15:06,792 --> 00:15:09,291
Look, I'm sure you're mad
I chucked you in the trash,

288
00:15:09,291 --> 00:15:11,709
but I've thought about it,
and I'm willing to forgive me.

289
00:15:11,709 --> 00:15:14,083
But the important thing is
the C.I.A. is looking for you.

290
00:15:14,083 --> 00:15:16,166
Oh, yeah? Bring 'em on!

291
00:15:16,166 --> 00:15:18,875
I got some stories to tell them
about who's been hiding me.

292
00:15:18,875 --> 00:15:22,000
Hope you and your family
like prison, because that's
where you'll be rotting.

293
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,166
In prison! That's who!

294
00:15:24,166 --> 00:15:26,959
Hey, I'm not
screwing around here. My butt
is literally on the line.

295
00:15:26,959 --> 00:15:31,125
Well, that must be one
massive line, because
your butt is huge!

296
00:15:31,125 --> 00:15:34,709
-(laughs)
-(line disconnects)

297
00:15:34,709 --> 00:15:39,834
So, old buddy,
to protect our family,
we must kill a friend.

298
00:15:39,834 --> 00:15:43,750
Don't worry. It's not you.
I could never be mad at you.

299
00:15:43,750 --> 00:15:47,166
Huh? Coochie-coochie.
Ha, ha! Made you laugh!

300
00:15:50,041 --> 00:15:52,750
Gun, we've got to track down
and kill Roger

301
00:15:52,750 --> 00:15:55,166
before the C.I.A. finds him.

302
00:15:55,166 --> 00:15:58,000
(sniffing)
Oh, gun!
Crack a window!

303
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,834
Boy, I really got up
in Stan's grille, huh?

304
00:16:00,834 --> 00:16:04,458
He was all, "Come back!"
And I was all,
"Fat-ass carpetbagger!"

305
00:16:04,458 --> 00:16:06,792
-(laughing)
-He had it comin'!

306
00:16:06,792 --> 00:16:09,542
That family don't give
a Dixie toot about you.

307
00:16:09,542 --> 00:16:11,750
From now on,
we're a family.

308
00:16:11,750 --> 00:16:14,709
We are, aren't we?
Oh, my God!

309
00:16:17,208 --> 00:16:20,000
A Dynasty exhibit.
They must've gotten
my letters.

310
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,250
Can we go? Can we go?
Can we go? Can we?

311
00:16:22,250 --> 00:16:25,875
Sounds glorious.
Let's get movin', sis.

312
00:16:25,875 --> 00:16:28,208
Oh, almost forgot.
(hawking)

313
00:16:28,208 --> 00:16:33,166
That's for freein' the slaves,
you Negro-lovin' Yankee devil!

314
00:16:35,083 --> 00:16:38,125
And suddenly
things turned ugly.

315
00:16:38,125 --> 00:16:40,291
Roger?
(whistles)

316
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:42,959
Here, boy! Damn it.
Where could he be?

317
00:16:42,959 --> 00:16:45,041
This ain't
your corner, bitch!

318
00:16:45,041 --> 00:16:47,834
Well, I guess my G.P.S.
is out of whack, slut!

319
00:16:47,834 --> 00:16:49,417
-Bitch!
-Slut!

320
00:16:49,417 --> 00:16:50,875
-Bitch!
-Slut!

321
00:16:50,875 --> 00:16:53,000
This reminds me of something.

322
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:55,959
(gasps)
Dynasty!

323
00:16:55,959 --> 00:16:59,417
C.I.A.
To the Smithsonian! Drive!

324
00:16:59,417 --> 00:17:02,208
Wait. This is my car.
Even better!

325
00:17:02,208 --> 00:17:05,583
Now, Son, here's a fun activity
my father taught me.

326
00:17:05,583 --> 00:17:07,917
But I feel weird
washing Mom's underwear.

327
00:17:07,917 --> 00:17:11,667
Nonsense!
We're bonding. Now bury me
in an avalanche of panties.

328
00:17:11,667 --> 00:17:15,250
Ja. Ja. Her sweaty,
sweaty sports bra!

329
00:17:15,250 --> 00:17:17,542
(cackling)

330
00:17:18,917 --> 00:17:21,250
Mom, you're reading
the Bible again!

331
00:17:21,250 --> 00:17:23,792
Oh, no.
There's an oil spill
in the garage.

332
00:17:23,792 --> 00:17:26,542
I'm just gonna mop it up
with Exodus.

333
00:17:26,542 --> 00:17:28,041
-(phone rings)
-Hello?

334
00:17:28,041 --> 00:17:30,041
Hayley? Roger.
Got a sec?

335
00:17:30,041 --> 00:17:31,959
Roger? Whoa!

336
00:17:31,959 --> 00:17:34,333
Is this one of those
Twilight Zone phones

337
00:17:34,333 --> 00:17:37,750
where I can talk to the dead
but only with horrible,
ironic consequences?

338
00:17:37,750 --> 00:17:40,166
Oh, right. It's past noon.
You're already high.

339
00:17:40,166 --> 00:17:41,959
Let me talk to the fish.

340
00:17:41,959 --> 00:17:44,041
Oh, my God!
You're really alive?

341
00:17:44,041 --> 00:17:47,625
Yes, and I've somehow acquired
a nasty, old, racist sidekick.

342
00:17:47,625 --> 00:17:50,166
I'm at the Smithsonian.
You gotta come get me.

343
00:17:50,166 --> 00:17:53,917
There you are. You send
me to get you a churro,
and then you disappear.

344
00:17:53,917 --> 00:17:57,542
-Anyway, here's your
filthy wetback doughnut.
-Hurry.

345
00:17:58,834 --> 00:18:00,917
(gasps)

346
00:18:00,917 --> 00:18:03,709
We've tracked the alien here.
We need to take it alive,

347
00:18:03,709 --> 00:18:06,500
so we can punish those
who've been hiding it.

348
00:18:07,792 --> 00:18:10,083
Not if I get to him first.

349
00:18:10,083 --> 00:18:13,417
Oh, my God!
Joan Collins's ball gown!

350
00:18:13,417 --> 00:18:17,583
Linda Evans's tennis outfit!
Wow! John Forsythe's girdle!

351
00:18:17,583 --> 00:18:20,000
Oh, the stories it could tell.

352
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,291
-STEVE: Roger?
-Steve! Hayley!

353
00:18:22,291 --> 00:18:24,125
Oh, thank God you came.

354
00:18:24,125 --> 00:18:27,083
Roger's alive?
It's a miracle!

355
00:18:27,083 --> 00:18:30,583
I knew you couldn't resist
a federally funded
Dynasty exhibit.

356
00:18:30,583 --> 00:18:33,083
Stan! Look,
about that phone call--

357
00:18:33,083 --> 00:18:34,834
-(gunshot)
-(screams) What are you doing?

358
00:18:34,834 --> 00:18:38,417
-Say your prayers, space chimp.
-Stan, no!

359
00:18:38,417 --> 00:18:40,125
Leave her alone,
whitey!

360
00:18:41,583 --> 00:18:46,250
-(gunshots continue)
-(both gasping)

361
00:18:55,625 --> 00:18:57,667
BULLOCK:
Damn it! He's getting away!

362
00:18:57,667 --> 00:18:59,959
DUPER:
Look, we're parachute ghosts!

363
00:18:59,959 --> 00:19:02,458
(making ghostly sounds)

364
00:19:06,667 --> 00:19:09,583
All this
for a "fat-ass" comment?

365
00:19:09,583 --> 00:19:11,959
No, former Dad!

366
00:19:11,959 --> 00:19:15,041
Nobody threatens my family.
Now get out of the way,
or I'll shoot you all.

367
00:19:15,041 --> 00:19:17,583
Oh, God, it's my junior prom
all over again.

368
00:19:17,583 --> 00:19:22,041
Leave her alone, you
two-dollar, pai-gow whore!

369
00:19:22,041 --> 00:19:24,291
(Gertie screaming)

370
00:19:24,291 --> 00:19:27,417
We know you're in there, alien!
Come out with your tentacles up!

371
00:19:27,417 --> 00:19:30,667
-Dad, you can't
just give him up!
-That's the C.I.A. out there.

372
00:19:30,667 --> 00:19:34,041
They won't stop until
they have Roger in custody.

373
00:19:34,041 --> 00:19:36,709
-Just make it quick.
-No, Roger!

374
00:19:36,709 --> 00:19:39,166
-Use my children as a shield!
-(both gasping)

375
00:19:39,166 --> 00:19:42,750
It's no use. They've got me.
If they torture me, I'll crack.

376
00:19:42,750 --> 00:19:46,500
I mean, I can't even
make it through the afternoon
without a freakin' mojito.

377
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:49,166
I'd never want to put
my family's safety at risk.

378
00:19:49,166 --> 00:19:52,458
-Your family?
-Of course. Now, how
are we gonna do this?

379
00:19:52,458 --> 00:19:55,041
I think right here
would be most dramatic.

380
00:19:55,041 --> 00:19:57,583
Okay. Huh?

381
00:19:57,583 --> 00:20:01,583
What's this? Some kind
of tear-like substance
coming from my eyes.

382
00:20:01,583 --> 00:20:03,583
-He's crying.
-I'm not a lady!

383
00:20:03,583 --> 00:20:06,959
Stan, having feelings
doesn't make you a lady.

384
00:20:06,959 --> 00:20:09,625
It makes you human.

385
00:20:09,625 --> 00:20:13,959
BULLOCK:
We've got to blow this door!
Prepare the door blower!

386
00:20:13,959 --> 00:20:15,875
We really should find
a better name for that.

387
00:20:15,875 --> 00:20:21,041
(sighs)
Well, it's clear
what I have to do.

388
00:20:21,041 --> 00:20:23,625
-Smith!
-I've got the alien, sir.

389
00:20:25,250 --> 00:20:28,083
Give me back my wig,
you scalp-happy red man!

390
00:20:28,083 --> 00:20:30,667
Look how it mimics
our language.

391
00:20:30,667 --> 00:20:32,792
(Gertie muttering)

392
00:20:32,792 --> 00:20:36,500
Well done, Agent Smith.
I'm going back to the office

393
00:20:36,500 --> 00:20:40,458
and striking the words
"tool" and "incompetent"
from your personal record.

394
00:20:40,458 --> 00:20:44,750
Thanks. Perhaps
you could insert the words
"lady" and "not a."

395
00:20:44,750 --> 00:20:47,750
You know,
I think we can.

396
00:20:50,834 --> 00:20:52,792
It's good to have you
back, buddy.

397
00:20:52,792 --> 00:20:54,792
So, Roger,
what was heaven like?

398
00:20:54,792 --> 00:20:57,667
-Heaven? Wh-What
the hell are you--
-(kicking)

399
00:20:57,667 --> 00:21:00,250
Oh, yeah, heaven.
Oh, oh, it was great.

400
00:21:00,250 --> 00:21:04,041
Fluffy clouds, unicorns,
bubble-gum waterfalls,
all that crap.

401
00:21:04,041 --> 00:21:06,750
Roger's our little miracle.
Isn't he, Mom?

402
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:11,166
He sure is. God certainly
works in mysterious ways.

403
00:21:11,166 --> 00:21:14,083
Oh, wait.
This is last month.

404
00:21:51,875 --> 00:21:53,834
Bye. Have a great time!

